(1014, 1, '2019-05-22 03:12:22', '2019-05-22 03:12:22', '[vc_row full_width="stretch_row" css=".vc_custom_1558486916688{background-color: #f6f6f6 !important;}"][vc_column][ultimate_heading main_heading="Distinguishing Between - Inert Information, Activated Ignorance, Activated Knowledge" margin_design_tab_text=""][/ultimate_heading][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1558487363798{margin-top: 40px !important;margin-bottom: 60px !important;}"]\n<div><span style="color: #808080;">It is impossible to reason without using some set of facts, data, or experiences as a constituent part of one’s thinking. Finding trustworthy sources of information and refining one’s own experience critically are important goals of critical thinkers. We must be vigilant about the sources of information we use. We must be analytically critical of the use we make of our own experience. Experience may be the best teacher, but biased experience supports bias, distorted experience supports distortion, self-deluded experience supports self-delusion. We, therefore, must not think of our experience as sacred in any way but, instead, as one important dimension of thought that must, like all others, be critically analyzed and assessed.</span></div>\n&nbsp;[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row full_width="stretch_row" css=".vc_custom_1558487428182{padding-top: 80px !important;padding-bottom: 40px !important;background-color: #ffffff !important;}"][vc_column width="1/3"][vc_single_image image="1006" img_size="full"][/vc_column][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_custom_heading text="Execution: Getting Things Done" font_container="tag:h2|font_size:30px|text_align:left" use_theme_fonts="yes"][vc_custom_heading text="sustainable enterprises and the Work Integrated Program." font_container="tag:h3|text_align:left|color:%234145ee" use_theme_fonts="yes"][vc_column_text]\n<div class="copyContainer">\n<div class="copyContainer">It’s Too Bad We Think of Execution as Something That Happens in Death Penalty States. Com